4.55/5  rDev +1.6%look: 4.25 | smell: 4.75 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.5Canned 04/10/17, pours cloudy gold orange color which looks like grapefruit juice that has a 1-2 finger foamy white head that was full of bubbles and faded very slowly, leaving good spotty lacing as it went down. Had a second can this evening and the lacing retention was much better.
Smells so fresh and juicy, it's like putting a hop cone in one nostril with a slice of orange peel in the other nostril. Super aromatics and quite fruity, there's lots of citrus here including pineapple, grapefruit, papaya, orange peel, tangerine, melon and any citrus hop adjective you can think of. I also got earthy notes like fresh cut grass, tea leaf, weed, musty old fruit similar to rotting apples, floral hops and some pine cone/piney hops. Trailing biscuit and toasted grains bring some wheat bread toast to the party and add balance for a terrific nose.
Tastes like fruit juice, all things citrus up front. Plenty of citrus hops with grapefruit, lemon, pineapple, mango, tangerine, orange juice, Orangina soda, and then peppery spices like coriander, white pepper and cinnamon mixed with light caramel, red grapefruit pith, sour green apple and zesty piney hops. The malt backbone is tame with biscuit, buttered wheat bread and toasted grains adding the malty balance, but this is basically a hop bomb that is bitter yet mellow and well balanced at the same time. The citrus complexities keep bringing everything together for an overall great flavor.
Mouthfeel is creamy, smooth and yet carries some prickly, fizzy carbonation that allows the bitterness to seem average while completely masking the 9.3% ABV. An impressive feat to make such a strong beer flow down so effortlessly, this was medium bodied, complex and extremely east to drink. Another great DIPA by Trillium, I really enjoyed this brew. 1,800 charactersCHickman, Apr 19, 2017
