3.87/5  rDev -13.6%look: 4 | smell: 3.75 | taste: 3.75 | feel: 4.75 |  overall: 3.75750ml bottle, dated 6.15.16, poured into a Trillium snifter glass. 
The beer pours a pale golden straw color, hazy and cloudy, a finger or so of soapy white head, moderate retention with large patches of soapy lace. The aroma is pretty intense, spicy, green, earthy, piney, light citrus and fruit, just dominantly resinous with a really big cereal grain backbone, really sturdy malt bill. The flavors are equally as demanding, lightly fruity hops, dominantly spicy and earthy, a touch floral but mostly grassy and resinous with a stale cracker malt backbone that isn't my favorite profile, but is also a good counterbalance to how all the hops. The mouthfeel is great, coating, medium body that is so smooth yet lively, crisp with a quenching finish that is lightly dry.
Verdict: A pretty solid DIPA, but I actually prefer Mettle to Heavy Mettle. Aside from Vicinity, I've found that many of the "Yeast Coast" IPAs tend to get overly aggressive and unbalanced after a certain ABV, usually around 8%. I am really starting to find myself enjoying the more delicate, balanced and complex IPAs that come in a lighter package. Sometimes less is more, and this one might be a bit too much. 1,185 characterskevanb, Jul 16, 2016
